Fast Second-Order Online Kernel Learning through Incremental Matrix Sketching and Decomposition

Dongxie Wen Renmin University of ChinaBeijingChina 2019202221@ruc.edu.cn ,  Xiao Zhang Renmin University of ChinaBeijingChina zhangx89@ruc.edu.cn  and  Zhewei Wei Renmin University of ChinaBeijingChina zhewei@ruc.edu.cn
(2018)
Abstract.

Online Kernel Learning (OKL) has attracted considerable research interest due to its promising predictive performance in streaming environments. Second-order approaches are particularly appealing for OKL as they often offer substantial improvements in regret guarantees. However, existing second-order OKL approaches suffer from at least quadratic time complexity with respect to the pre-set budget, rendering them unsuitable for meeting the real-time demands of large-scale streaming recommender systems. The singular value decomposition required to obtain explicit feature mapping is also computationally expensive due to the complete decomposition process. Moreover, the absence of incremental updates to manage approximate kernel space causes these algorithms to perform poorly in adversarial environments and real-world streaming recommendation datasets. To address these issues, we propose FORKS, a fast incremental matrix sketching and decomposition approach tailored for second-order OKL. FORKS constructs an incremental maintenance paradigm for second-order kernelized gradient descent, which includes incremental matrix sketching for kernel approximation and incremental matrix decomposition for explicit feature mapping construction. Theoretical analysis demonstrates that FORKS achieves a logarithmic regret guarantee on par with other second-order approaches while maintaining a linear time complexity w.r.t. the budget, significantly enhancing efficiency over existing approaches. We validate the performance of FORKS through extensive experiments conducted on real-world streaming recommendation datasets, demonstrating its superior scalability and robustness against adversarial attacks.

online kernel learning; matrix sketching; streaming recommendation

1. Introduction

Online learning has been extensively applied in streaming recommender systems, where models require frequent updates based on real-time user feedback. In these settings, the processes of training and testing are interwoven (Shalev-Shwartz, 2011; Chandramouli et al., 2011; Chang et al., 2017; Wang et al., 2018b; Jakomin et al., 2020; Zhang et al., 2021; Wang et al., 2018a). A widely adopted algorithm in this domain is Online Gradient Descent (OGD), which iteratively adjusts model parameters by moving in the direction of the negative gradient to minimize the loss function (Zinkevich, 2003). However, OGD is limited by its reliance on linear combinations of input features, which can be insufficient for capturing complex patterns in real-world streaming recommendation scenarios. To address this shortcoming, Online Kernel Learning (OKL) extends OGD by mapping input features into a high-dimensional reproducing kernel Hilbert space (RKHS), enabling more effective handling of nonlinear learning tasks (Kivinen et al., 2004; Lu et al., 2016b; Singh et al., 2012; Sahoo et al., 2019; Hu et al., 2015).

OKL can be categorized into first-order and second-order approaches. First-order algorithms use a fixed learning rate for gradient descent, resulting in O⁢(T)𝑂𝑇O(\sqrt{T})italic_O ( square-root start_ARG italic_T end_ARG ) regret for any arbitrary sequence of convex losses (Lu et al., 2016b; Cavallanti et al., 2007; Zhao et al., 2012; Orabona et al., 2008; Zhang and Liao, 2019), where T𝑇Titalic_T denotes the number of rounds. Although some works set a more aggressive learning rate to improve the regret bound to O⁢(log⁡T)𝑂𝑇O(\log T)italic_O ( roman_log italic_T ), it requires the assumption that the loss function exhibits strong convexity, which is unrealistic for most loss functions (Zhu and Xu, 2015). In contrast, second-order algorithms utilize the Hessian matrix to adapt the learning rate, achieving logarithmic regret without requiring strong convexity in all directions (Calandriello et al., 2017b, a; Zhdanov and Kalnishkan, 2013; Hazan et al., 2007).

Despite its improved regret bounds, second-order Online Kernel Learning (OKL) encounters two significant challenges in streaming recommendation systems. First, streaming recommendation applications demand both efficient updates and minimal storage consumption. However, exact second-order OKL incurs O⁢(t2)𝑂superscript𝑡2O(t^{2})italic_O ( italic_t start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) space and time complexity at round t𝑡titalic_t, as it requires storing the entire kernel matrix (Hazan et al., 2007; Zhdanov and Kalnishkan, 2013). While some methods employ online sampling techniques to improve efficiency, these approaches primarily focus on kernel matrix approximation and fail to effectively obtain explicit feature mappings (Calandriello et al., 2017a, b). Specifically, these methods rely on complete singular value decomposition (SVD) to derive explicit feature mappings, which is computationally expensive. Second, real-world applications are often dynamic, reflecting the evolving interests of users over time. For instance, studies have shown that user click behaviors for news articles change over time in both Google News (Liu et al., 2010) and Yahoo News (Zeng et al., 2016). Without the capability to perform incremental updates in the approximate kernel matrix, existing algorithms risk making suboptimal decisions based on outdated information.

In this paper, we propose a fast incremental matrix sketching approach for second-order online kernel learning, along with an efficient decomposition method designed for incremental updates, effectively addressing the two aforementioned challenges both theoretically and experimentally. Our contributions can be summarized as follows:

  • •

    We propose FORKS, a fast and effective second-order online kernel learning method that can be generalized to both regression and classification tasks in streaming recommendation. FORKS maintains incremental matrix sketching using efficient low-rank modifications and constructs an effective time-varying explicit feature mapping. We provide a detailed theoretical analysis to illustrate the advantages of FORKS, including having linear time complexity w.r.t. the budget, and enjoying a logarithmic regret bound.

  • •

    We propose TISVD, a novel Truncated Incremental Singular Value Decomposition adapting to matrix decomposition problems in online learning environments. We theoretically compare the time complexity between TISVD and the original truncated low-rank SVD, confirming that FORKS with TISVD is computationally more efficient without compromising prediction performance.

  • •

    We conduct extensive experiments to demonstrate the superior performance of FORKS on both adversarial and real-world datasets, while also enhancing efficiency. Furthermore, we validate FORKS’s robustness and scalability using a large-scale streaming recommendation dataset.

2. Preliminaries

In this section, we introduce the online kernel learning problem and the matrix sketching technique to approximate the kernel matrix. Table 1 summarizes the notations used throughout this paper.

2.1. Online Kernel Learning

Streaming recommendations can be framed as an online kernel learning problem. Specifically, when a user interacts with the application, the input space 𝒳𝒳\mathcal{X}caligraphic_X encapsulates information about both the user and the items they have interacted with. Given a reproducing kernel Hilbert space (RKHS) ℋℋ\mathcal{H}caligraphic_H, we can define an associated feature map ϕbold-italic-ϕ\bm{\phi}bold_italic_ϕ to transform the input data. Using this feature map, we construct a hypothesis function f𝑓fitalic_f in the RKHS to predict the unknown label—such as the user’s click behavior. Finally, the true label y𝑦yitalic_y, based on user feedback, is received and used to update the current hypothesis.

In the t𝑡titalic_t-th user session (i.e., the t𝑡titalic_t-th round), the agent interacts with one user (i.e., predicts the click behavior of the user in an online manner).

2.2. Matrix Sketching

Given a matrix 𝑴∈ℝa×b𝑴superscriptℝ𝑎𝑏\bm{M}\in\mathbb{R}^{a\times{b}}bold_italic_M ∈ blackboard_R start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_a × italic_b end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, the sketch of 𝑴𝑴\bm{M}bold_italic_M is defined as 𝑴⁢𝑺∈ℝa×s𝑴𝑺superscriptℝ𝑎𝑠\bm{M}\bm{S}\in{\mathbb{R}^{a\times{s}}}bold_italic_M bold_italic_S ∈ blackboard_R start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_a × italic_s end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, where 𝑺∈ℝb×s𝑺superscriptℝ𝑏𝑠\bm{S}\in\mathbb{R}^{b\times{s}}bold_italic_S ∈ blackboard_R start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_b × italic_s end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT is a sketch matrix. In this paper, we introduce the Sparse Johnson-Lindenstrauss Transform and Column-sampling matrix as the sketch matrix (Charikar et al., 2002; Kane and Nelson, 2014).

3. FORKS: The Proposed Algorithm

In this section, we propose a novel efficient second-order online kernel learning method tailored for streaming recommendation with incremental sketching and decomposition, called FORKS.

3.1. Algorithm Overview

The streaming recommendation system needs to meet the demands of real-time performance and robustness. Figure 1 depicts the overall architecture of FORKS. Rather than storing the entire kernel matrix, we apply matrix sketching techniques to approximate it with constant size. Additionally, the novel truncated incremental singular value decomposition (TISVD) method is used to generate time-varying feature mappings. This leads to incremental maintenance of both the approximate kernel matrix and the approximate feature mapping, greatly boosting efficiency. Furthermore, user feedback and interaction history are used to incrementally update the approximate kernel space, allowing the algorithm to adapt to shifts in user preferences.

3.2. Matrix Sketching for Kernel Matrix Approximation

The size of the kernel matrix grows linearly with the number of rounds, making it unsuitable for meeting the real-time demands of streaming recommendation systems. Thus, it is necessary to approximate the kernel matrix.

Given the kernel matrix 𝑲(t)∈ℝt×tsuperscript𝑲𝑡superscriptℝ𝑡𝑡\bm{K}^{(t)}\in{\mathbb{R}^{t\times{t}}}bold_italic_K start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_t ) end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ∈ blackboard_R start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_t × italic_t end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, the prototype model (Williams and Seeger, 2000) get the approximate kernel matrix 𝑲^(t)=𝑪⁢𝑼fast⁢𝑪⊤superscript^𝑲𝑡𝑪subscript𝑼fastsuperscript𝑪top\hat{\bm{K}}^{(t)}=\bm{C}\bm{U}_{\text{fast}}\bm{C}^{\top}over^ start_ARG bold_italic_K end_ARG start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_t ) end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT = bold_italic_C bold_italic_U start_POSTSUBSCRIPT fast end_POSTSUBSCRIPT bold_italic_C start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ⊤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT by solving the following problem at round t𝑡titalic_t:

3.3. Novel Incremental Matrix Decomposition Method for Feature Mapping

In the previous section, we employed rank-k𝑘kitalic_k SVD to obtain the time-varying feature mapping; however, this method has proven inefficient in online environments. Specifically, standard rank-k𝑘kitalic_k SVD incurs a time complexity of O⁢(sp3)𝑂superscriptsubscript𝑠𝑝3O(s_{p}^{3})italic_O ( italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) for each update round, rendering it impractical in scenarios with a high volume of updates.

To overcome these limitations, we propose TISVD (Truncated Incremental Singular Value Decomposition), a novel incremental SVD method specifically designed for decomposing kernel sketches. TISVD provides linear time and space complexity with respect to the sketch size spsubscript𝑠𝑝s_{p}italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT.

We will begin by presenting the construction of TISVD, which is well-suited for decomposing matrices with low-rank update properties. Without loss of generality, we denote a matrix at round t𝑡titalic_t as

We summarize the above steps as Algorithm 1. Then, we will elucidate how TISVD can be employed in the context of online kernel learning, leading to a substantial reduction in the computational overhead associated with updating feature mapping.

TISVD efficiently constructs the feature mapping in linear time, eliminating the need to store the entire matrix. This renders it a practical decomposition scheme for OKL. The further discussions are presented in Appendix B due to space constraints.

3.4. Efficient Second-Order Online Kernel Learning

Since the efficient time-varying explicit feature mapping ϕt⁢(⋅)subscriptbold-italic-ϕ𝑡⋅\bm{\phi}_{t}(\cdot)bold_italic_ϕ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( ⋅ ) has been constructed, we can formulate the approximate hypothesis ft⁢(𝒙t)subscript𝑓𝑡subscript𝒙𝑡f_{t}(\bm{x}_{t})italic_f start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( bold_italic_x start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) at round t𝑡titalic_t that is closed to the optimal hypothesis, i.e.,

ft⁢(𝒙t)=𝒘t⊤⁢ϕt⁢(𝒙t),subscript𝑓𝑡subscript𝒙𝑡superscriptsubscript𝒘𝑡topsubscriptbold-italic-ϕ𝑡subscript𝒙𝑡f_{t}(\bm{x}_{t})=\bm{w}_{t}^{\top}\bm{\phi}_{t}(\bm{x}_{t}),italic_f start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( bold_italic_x start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) = bold_italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ⊤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT bold_italic_ϕ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( bold_italic_x start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) ,

where 𝒘tsubscript𝒘𝑡\bm{w}_{t}bold_italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT is the weight vector. On the basis of the hypothesis, we propose a two-stage online kernel learning procedure that follows the second-order update rules, named FORKS (Fast Second-Order Online Kernel Learning Using Incremental Sketching).

In the first stage, we simply collect the items with nonzero losses to the buffer SV and perform the Kernelized Online Gradient Descent (KOGD) (Kivinen et al., 2004). When the size of the buffer reaches a fixed budget B𝐵Bitalic_B, we calculate 𝑲tsubscript𝑲𝑡\bm{K}_{t}bold_italic_K start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and initialize sketch matrices 𝚽p⁢p(t),𝚽p⁢m(t)superscriptsubscript𝚽𝑝𝑝𝑡superscriptsubscript𝚽𝑝𝑚𝑡\bm{\Phi}_{pp}^{(t)},\bm{\Phi}_{pm}^{(t)}bold_Φ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_t ) end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT , bold_Φ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_t ) end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT in Eq. (3).

In the second stage, we adopt a periodic updating strategy for sketches. More precisely, we update 𝚽p⁢p(t)superscriptsubscript𝚽𝑝𝑝𝑡\bm{\Phi}_{pp}^{(t)}bold_Φ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_t ) end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, 𝚽p⁢m(t)superscriptsubscript𝚽𝑝𝑚𝑡\bm{\Phi}_{pm}^{(t)}bold_Φ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_t ) end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT by Eq. (11) (details in Appendix A) once for every ρ𝜌\rhoitalic_ρ examples, where ρ∈[T−B]𝜌delimited-[]𝑇𝐵\rho\in[T-B]italic_ρ ∈ [ italic_T - italic_B ] is defined as update cycle. Furthermore, we incrementally update the feature mapping ϕt⁢(⋅)subscriptbold-italic-ϕ𝑡⋅\bm{\phi}_{t}(\cdot)bold_italic_ϕ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( ⋅ ) by TISVD.

In addition to updating the feature mapping ϕt⁢(⋅)subscriptbold-italic-ϕ𝑡⋅\bm{\phi}_{t}(\cdot)bold_italic_ϕ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( ⋅ ), we perform second-order updates on the 𝒘tsubscript𝒘𝑡\bm{w}_{t}bold_italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. The second-order updates not only consider the gradient information but also utilize the curvature information of the loss function, leading to faster convergence rates.

At the start of a new update epoch, we incorporate a reset step before applying the gradient descent in the new embedded space. We update the feature mapping ϕtsubscriptbold-italic-ϕ𝑡\bm{\phi}_{t}bold_italic_ϕ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT but reset 𝑨tsubscript𝑨𝑡\bm{A}_{t}bold_italic_A start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and 𝒘tsubscript𝒘𝑡\bm{w}_{t}bold_italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. This step is taken to ensure that our starting point cannot be influenced by the adversary. By leveraging efficient second-order updates, we can effectively converge to the optimal hypothesis within the current subspace. Furthermore, the reset of the descent procedure when transitioning between subspaces ensures a stable starting point and maintains a bounded regret throughout the entire process. We summarize the above stages into Algorithm 2.

The incremental update of the feature mapping, combined with the reset mechanism, ensures that we can effectively capture changes in user preferences over time. More specifically, our algorithm updates the feature vector to reflect the user’s current state, while resetting the Hessian matrix mitigates the influence of outdated data on the learner.

3.5. Complexity Analysis of FORKS

Given the budget of B𝐵Bitalic_B, our FORKS consists of three parts: (1) the first stage using KOGD, (2) the updating round in the second stage, and (3) the regular round in the second stage. At the first stage (|S⁢V|≤B)𝑆𝑉𝐵(|SV|\leq B)( | italic_S italic_V | ≤ italic_B ), FORKS has constant time O⁢(B)𝑂𝐵O(B)italic_O ( italic_B ) and space complexities O⁢(B)𝑂𝐵O(B)italic_O ( italic_B ) per round.

The main computational complexity of FORKS during the update round stems from the matrix decomposition and inversion procedures. These processes are necessary for updating the feature mapping and performing second-order gradient updates, respectively. Our proposed TISVD reduce the time complexity of 𝚽p⁢psubscript𝚽𝑝𝑝\bm{\Phi}_{pp}bold_Φ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT decomposition from O⁢(sp3)𝑂superscriptsubscript𝑠𝑝3O\left(s_{p}^{3}\right)italic_O ( italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) to O⁢(sp⁢k+k3)𝑂subscript𝑠𝑝𝑘superscript𝑘3O\left(s_{p}k+k^{3}\right)italic_O ( italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_k + italic_k start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ), where spsubscript𝑠𝑝s_{p}italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT is the sketch size of 𝑺psubscript𝑺𝑝\bm{S}_{p}bold_italic_S start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT and k𝑘kitalic_k is the rank in TISVD. A naive implementation of the second-order update requires O⁢(k3)𝑂superscript𝑘3O\left(k^{3}\right)italic_O ( italic_k start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) per-step time and has a space complexity of O⁢(k2)𝑂superscript𝑘2O\left(k^{2}\right)italic_O ( italic_k start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) necessary to store the Hessian 𝑨tsubscript𝑨𝑡\bm{A}_{t}bold_italic_A start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. However, by taking advantage of the fact that 𝑨tsubscript𝑨𝑡\bm{A}_{t}bold_italic_A start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT is constructed using rank-1111 modification, we can reduce the per-step cost to O⁢(k2)𝑂superscript𝑘2O\left(k^{2}\right)italic_O ( italic_k start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ). We denote the update cycle as ρ𝜌\rhoitalic_ρ and μ=B+⌊T−Bρ⌋𝜇𝐵𝑇𝐵𝜌\mu=B+\left\lfloor{\frac{T-B}{\rho}}\right\rflooritalic_μ = italic_B + ⌊ divide start_ARG italic_T - italic_B end_ARG start_ARG italic_ρ end_ARG ⌋. To summarize, the time complexity of FORKS at each updating round is O⁢(μ+sp⁢k2+sm⁢sp⁢k+k3)𝑂𝜇subscript𝑠𝑝superscript𝑘2subscript𝑠𝑚subscript𝑠𝑝𝑘superscript𝑘3O\left(\mu+s_{p}k^{2}+s_{m}s_{p}k+k^{3}\right)italic_O ( italic_μ + italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_k start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT + italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_k + italic_k start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ), and the space complexity is O⁢(μ+sp⁢k+sm⁢sp+k2)𝑂𝜇subscript𝑠𝑝𝑘subscript𝑠𝑚subscript𝑠𝑝superscript𝑘2O\left(\mu+s_{p}k+s_{m}s_{p}+k^{2}\right)italic_O ( italic_μ + italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_k + italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT + italic_k start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ), where smsubscript𝑠𝑚s_{m}italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT is the sketch size of 𝑺msubscript𝑺𝑚\bm{S}_{m}bold_italic_S start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT.

The primary time consumption for the online learning algorithm occurs during regular rounds. At each regular round, the time complexity of FORKS is O⁢(sm⁢k+k2)𝑂subscript𝑠𝑚𝑘superscript𝑘2O\left(s_{m}k+k^{2}\right)italic_O ( italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_k + italic_k start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ). Given that sm<sp<Bsubscript𝑠𝑚subscript𝑠𝑝𝐵s_{m}<s_{p}<Bitalic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT < italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT < italic_B, our algorithm achieves a time complexity of O⁢(B⁢k+k2)𝑂𝐵𝑘superscript𝑘2O\left(Bk+k^{2}\right)italic_O ( italic_B italic_k + italic_k start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) per step. The current state-of-the-art second-order online kernel learning method, PROS-N-KONS, presents a time complexity of O⁢(B2)𝑂superscript𝐵2O\left(B^{2}\right)italic_O ( italic_B start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) per step in its budget version (Calandriello et al., 2017a). Moreover, due to the changing size of the subspace from online sampling, PROS-N-KONS must perform a complete SVD at each step. In contrast, FORKS introduces substantial advancements by reducing the time complexity from O⁢(B2)𝑂superscript𝐵2O\left(B^{2}\right)italic_O ( italic_B start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) to O⁢(B⁢k+k2)𝑂𝐵𝑘superscript𝑘2O\left(Bk+k^{2}\right)italic_O ( italic_B italic_k + italic_k start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ).

4. Regret Analysis

In this section, we provide the regret analysis for the proposed second-order online kernel learning algorithm. We begin by making the following assumptions about the loss functions.

Assumption 1 (Lipschitz Continuity).

In practical scenarios, the assumption of strong convexity may not always hold as it imposes constraints on the convexity of losses in all directions. A more feasible approach is to relax this assumption by demanding strong convexity only in the gradient direction, which is a weaker condition as indicated by the two assumptions above. For example, exp-concave losses like squared loss and squared hinge loss satisfy the condition in Assumption 2.

The conditions stated in Assumption 3 can be satisfied by several sketch matrices, such as SJLT (Woodruff, 2014). proof sketch.

ℓt⁢(𝒘t)−ℓt⁢(𝒘t∗)⏟Term 1: Optimization Error+ℓt⁢(𝒘t∗)−ℓt⁢(𝒘∗)⏟Term 2: Estimation Error,subscript⏟subscriptℓ𝑡subscript𝒘𝑡subscriptℓ𝑡superscriptsubscript𝒘𝑡Term 1: Optimization Errorsubscript⏟subscriptℓ𝑡superscriptsubscript𝒘𝑡subscriptℓ𝑡superscript𝒘Term 2: Estimation Error\displaystyle\underbrace{\ell_{t}(\bm{w}_{t})-\ell_{t}(\bm{w}_{t}^{*})}_{\text% {Term 1: Optimization Error}}+\underbrace{\ell_{t}(\bm{w}_{t}^{*})-\ell_{t}(% \bm{w}^{*})}_{\text{Term 2: Estimation Error}},under⏟ start_ARG roman_ℓ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( bold_italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) - roman_ℓ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( bold_italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ∗ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT Term 1: Optimization Error end_POSTSUBSCRIPT + under⏟ start_ARG roman_ℓ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( bold_italic_w start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ∗ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) - roman_ℓ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( bold_italic_w start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ∗ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ) end_ARG start_POSTSUBSCRIPT Term 2: Estimation Error end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ,

where 𝒘∗superscript𝒘\bm{w}^{*}bold_italic_w start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ∗ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT denotes the optimal hypothesis on the incremental sketches in hindsight. The optimization error arises from the optimization step of second-order online gradient descent, while the estimation error is due to the incremental matrix sketching and the truncated singular values in TISVD. We then bound these errors and complete the proof. The full proof is provided in Appendix C.

∎

Remark 1.

In Theorem 1, the assumption of polynomial eigenvalue decay for the kernel matrix is broadly applicable and satisfied by various types of kernels, including shift-invariant, finite-rank, and convolution kernels (Liu and Liao, 2015; Belkin, 2018). This decay property ensures that the accumulated truncated singular values of TISVD can be effectively bounded by the number of update rounds.

Remark 2.

It’s worth noting that when LCur=0subscript𝐿Cur0L_{\mathrm{Cur}}=0italic_L start_POSTSUBSCRIPT roman_Cur end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 0, Assumption 2 essentially enforces convexity. In the worst case when LCur=0subscript𝐿Cur0L_{\mathrm{Cur}}=0italic_L start_POSTSUBSCRIPT roman_Cur end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 0, the regret bound in the convex case degenerates to O⁢(T)𝑂𝑇O(\sqrt{T})italic_O ( square-root start_ARG italic_T end_ARG ). The detailed proof is included in Appendix D.

By configuring the update cycle as ρ=⌊θ⁢(T−B)⌋𝜌𝜃𝑇𝐵\rho=\lfloor\theta(T-B)\rflooritalic_ρ = ⌊ italic_θ ( italic_T - italic_B ) ⌋, where θ∈(0,1)𝜃01\theta\in(0,1)italic_θ ∈ ( 0 , 1 ), and setting the sketch size ratio to γ=O⁢(log⁡(T)/T)𝛾𝑂𝑇𝑇\gamma=O(\log(T)/\sqrt{T})italic_γ = italic_O ( roman_log ( italic_T ) / square-root start_ARG italic_T end_ARG ), we derive an upper bound on regret of O⁢(T14⁢log⁡T)𝑂superscript𝑇14𝑇O\left(T^{\frac{1}{4}}\log T\right)italic_O ( italic_T start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT divide start_ARG 1 end_ARG start_ARG 4 end_ARG end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT roman_log italic_T ) for second-order online kernel learning. In contrast, the regret bound for first-order online kernel learning is O⁢(T)𝑂𝑇O(\sqrt{T})italic_O ( square-root start_ARG italic_T end_ARG ), while requiring a budget of B=O⁢(T)𝐵𝑂𝑇B=O(T)italic_B = italic_O ( italic_T ) (Lu et al., 2016a), making it less favorable than FORKS. Under the same assumption that the eigenvalues decay polynomially with rate β𝛽\betaitalic_β, the regret bound for existing second-order online kernel learning via online sampling is O⁢(T1β⁢log2⁡T)𝑂superscript𝑇1𝛽superscript2𝑇O\left(T^{\frac{1}{\beta}}\log^{2}T\right)italic_O ( italic_T start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT divide start_ARG 1 end_ARG start_ARG italic_β end_ARG end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT roman_log start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_T ) (Calandriello et al., 2017a). Note that the regret and complexity of PROS-N-KONS are highly dependent on the eigenvalue decay rate. In practice, ensuring a rapid decay of the kernel matrix is unrealistic for streaming recommendation systems. When the matrix properties are less favorable (e.g., β<4𝛽4\beta<4italic_β < 4), the regret of PROS-N-KONS can be worse than that of FORKS. To support our analysis, we conduct an experiment on a streaming recommendation dataset, as detailed in Section 5.3.

5. Experiments

In this section, we conduct experiments to evaluate the performance of FORKS on a wide variety of datasets. The details of datasets and experimental setup are presented in Appendix E, F.

5.1. Experiments under a Fixed Budget

In this section, we demonstrate the performance of FORKS under a fixed budget, employing six widely recognized classification benchmark datasets. We compare FORKS with the existing budgeted-based online learning algorithms, including first-order algorithms RBP (Cavallanti et al., 2007), BPA-S (Wang and Vucetic, 2010), BOGD (Zhao et al., 2012), FOGD, NOGD (Lu et al., 2016a), Projectron (Orabona et al., 2008), SkeGD (Zhang and Liao, 2019) and second-order algorithm PROS-N-KONS (Calandriello et al., 2017a). We implement the above models with the help of the LIBOL v0.3.0 toolbox toolbox 111http://libol.stevenhoi.org/. All algorithms are trained using hinge loss, and their performance is measured by the average online mistake rate.

For all the algorithms, we set a fixed budget B=50𝐵50B=50italic_B = 50 for small datasets (N≤10000)𝑁10000(N\leq 10000)( italic_N ≤ 10000 ) and B=100𝐵100B=100italic_B = 100 for large datasets. Furthermore, we set buffer size B~=2⁢B,γ=0.2formulae-sequence~𝐵2𝐵𝛾0.2\tilde{B}=2B,\gamma=0.2over~ start_ARG italic_B end_ARG = 2 italic_B , italic_γ = 0.2, sp=Bsubscript𝑠𝑝𝐵s_{p}=Bitalic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = italic_B, sm=γ⁢spsubscript𝑠𝑚𝛾subscript𝑠𝑝s_{m}=\gamma{s_{p}}italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = italic_γ italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT, θ=0.3𝜃0.3\theta=0.3italic_θ = 0.3, and update cycle ρ=⌊θ⁢N⌋𝜌𝜃𝑁\rho=\lfloor\theta{N}\rflooritalic_ρ = ⌊ italic_θ italic_N ⌋ in SkeGD and FORKS if not specially specified. For algorithms with rank-k𝑘kitalic_k approximation, we uniformly set k=0.1⁢B𝑘0.1𝐵k=0.1Bitalic_k = 0.1 italic_B. Besides, we use the same experimental settings for FOGD (feature dimension = 4B). The results are presented in Table 2. Our FORKS shows the best performance on most datasets and the suboptimal performance on german and ijcnn1. The update time of FORKS is comparable to that of the majority of first-order algorithms, including NOGD and SkeGD. Besides, FORKS is significantly more efficient than the existing second-order method PROS-N-KONS in large-scale datasets such as codrna and w7a.

Then, we conduct experiments to evaluate how TISVD affects the performance of the algorithm. We use the same experimental setup in codrna and vary the update rate θ𝜃\thetaitalic_θ from 0.5 to 0.0005. Figure 2 demonstrates that TISVD maintains efficient decomposition speed without excessively reducing performance. Furthermore, considering that frequent updates can potentially result in an elevated loss, it is essential to carefully choose an optimal update cycle that strikes a balance between achieving superior accuracy and maintaining efficiency.

5.2. Experiments under Adversarial Environment

To empirically validate the algorithms under an adversarial environment, we build adversarial datasets using the benchmark codrna and german. We compare FORKS with first-order algorithms BOGD (Zhao et al., 2012), SkeGD (Zhang and Liao, 2019), NOGD (Lu et al., 2016a) and second-order algorithm PROS-N-KONS (Calandriello et al., 2017a) under the same budget B=200𝐵200B=200italic_B = 200. Besides, we set γ=0.2𝛾0.2\gamma=0.2italic_γ = 0.2, sp=0.75⁢Bsubscript𝑠𝑝0.75𝐵s_{p}=0.75Bitalic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 0.75 italic_B, sm=γ⁢sp,k=0.1⁢Bformulae-sequencesubscript𝑠𝑚𝛾subscript𝑠𝑝𝑘0.1𝐵s_{m}=\gamma{s_{p}},k=0.1Bitalic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_m end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = italic_γ italic_s start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , italic_k = 0.1 italic_B and update cycle ρ=⌊0.005⁢(N−B)⌋𝜌0.005𝑁𝐵\rho=\lfloor 0.005(N-B)\rflooritalic_ρ = ⌊ 0.005 ( italic_N - italic_B ) ⌋ in SkeGD and FORKS. Inspired by the adversarial settings in (Calandriello et al., 2017a; Zhang and Liao, 2019; Wang et al., 2018c), we generate an online learning game with b𝑏bitalic_b blocks. At each block, we extract an instance from the dataset and repeat it for r𝑟ritalic_r rounds. In addition, the labels are flipped in each even block by multiplying them with -1. We set b=500𝑏500b=500italic_b = 500, r=10𝑟10r=10italic_r = 10 for codrna-1 and german-1.

Experimental results are presented in Table 3. It is observed that in the adversarial environment, the performance of all methods significantly decreases with the increase of adversarial changes except for FORKS. This is due to the fact that FORKS accurately captures the concept drifting through the incremental update of the sketch matrix and the execution of rapid second-order gradient descent. Moreover, FORKS maintains its efficiency comparable to first-order algorithms, thereby ensuring that improved performance is achieved without sacrificing computational time.

5.3. Experiments on Large-Scale Datasets

In this experiment, we evaluate the efficiency and effectiveness of FORKS on streaming recommendation. We use KuaiRec, which is a real-world dataset collected from the recommendation logs of the video-sharing mobile app Kuaishou (Gao et al., 2022). We conduct experiments on the dense matrix of KuaiRec, which consists of 4,494,57844945784,494,5784 , 494 , 578 instances with associated timestamps, making it an ideal benchmark for evaluating large-scale online learning tasks. We test the performance of the algorithm used in Section 5.3 under different budgets B𝐵Bitalic_B ranging from 100100100100 to 500500500500. To avoid excessive training time, we use a budgeted version of PROS-N-KONS that stops updating the dictionary at a maximum budget of Bmax=100subscript𝐵100B_{\max}=100italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT roman_max end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 100. Since the buffer size of PROS-N-KONS is data-dependent, we repeat the training process 20 times to compute the average error rate and the average time for comparison. In addition to the hinge loss, we use squared hinge loss to evaluate the performance of algorithms.

Figure 3 (a) shows the tradeoff between running time and the average mistake rate in the experiment using hinge loss. Figure 3 (b) shows the tradeoff between running time and the average mistake rate in the experiment using squared hinge loss. We observe that FORKS consistently achieves superior learning performance while maintaining comparable time costs to the other first-order algorithms, regardless of the loss function’s shape. In particular, for squared hinge loss, both PROS-N-KONS and FORKS significantly outperform first-order models, highlighting the advantages of second-order methods under exp-concave losses. Additionally, we note that FORKS exhibits significantly higher efficiency compared to the second-order algorithm PROS-N-KONS. In fact, to achieve a similar online error rate, FORKS speeds up the running time by a factor of 3333.

6. Conclusion

This paper introduces FORKS, a fast second-order online kernel learning approach. FORKS leverages incremental sketching and decomposition to efficiently manage the complex computations involved in kernel feature mapping and hypothesis updates, addressing the challenges of applying it to streaming recommendation systems. FORKS achieves a logarithmic regret bound while maintaining linear time complexity with respect to the budget. Extensive experiments on real-world datasets validate the superior scalability and robustness of FORKS, highlighting its potential for streaming recommendation tasks.

Appendix B More Discussion about TISVD

Current incremental SVD methods necessitate the prerequisite that the decomposition matrix adheres to a low-rank structure (Brand, 2006). When this low-rank condition isn’t met, these methods devolve into traditional SVD. However, in online learning scenarios, the assurance of a low-rank decomposed sketch matrix isn’t guaranteed. In this context, TISVD innovatively accomplishes incremental maintenance of singular value matrices without relying on low-rank assumptions, rendering it adapt to online learning algorithms founded on incremental sketching methodologies.

More precisely, given the matrix 𝑨=𝑼⁢𝚺⁢𝑽⊤∈ℝn×n𝑨𝑼𝚺superscript𝑽topsuperscriptℝ𝑛𝑛\bm{A}=\bm{U}\bm{\Sigma}\bm{V}^{\top}\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times{n}}bold_italic_A = bold_italic_U bold_Σ bold_italic_V start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ⊤ end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ∈ blackboard_R start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_n × italic_n end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, the conventional incremental SVD (ISVD) streamlines the process by omitting the rotation and re-orthogonalization of 𝑼𝑼\bm{U}bold_italic_U and 𝑽𝑽\bm{V}bold_italic_V, leading to a time complexity of O⁢(n⁢r+r3)𝑂𝑛𝑟superscript𝑟3O(nr+r^{3})italic_O ( italic_n italic_r + italic_r start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ). where r𝑟ritalic_r denotes the matrix rank. Consequently, ISVD relies on the assumption that r≪nmuch-less-than𝑟𝑛r\ll{n}italic_r ≪ italic_n in order to effectively establish a linear-time SVD algorithm.

Nevertheless, in online learning scenarios, the sketch matrix earmarked for decomposition frequently fails to adhere to the low-rank characteristic, thereby rendering the direct application of ISVD ineffective in achieving linear time complexity. To counter this predicament, we have integrated truncation techniques within the framework of traditional incremental SVD methods. This adaptation yields a time complexity of O⁢(n⁢rt+rt3)𝑂𝑛subscript𝑟𝑡superscriptsubscript𝑟𝑡3O(nr_{t}+r_{t}^{3})italic_O ( italic_n italic_r start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT + italic_r start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ), with rtsubscript𝑟𝑡r_{t}italic_r start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_t end_POSTSUBSCRIPT signifying the predetermined truncated rank. Crucially, this truncation innovation positions TISVD as a linear incremental SVD technique that stands independent of low-rank assumptions.

As previously discussed, applying ISVD directly to online learning algorithms isn’t viable. Recognizing the substantial enhancement that accelerated decomposition feature mapping can offer to the performance of online kernel learning algorithms, prevailing research employs the randomized SVD algorithm to expedite these algorithms (Wan and Zhang, 2021; Zhang and Liao, 2019). However, it’s important to highlight that, unlike the incremental SVD method, the randomized SVD is a rapid SVD technique reliant on random matrices and lacks the capability to perform incremental updates on singular value matrices. Furthermore, it’s worth noting that the time complexity of randomized SVD is O⁢(n2⁢r+r3)𝑂superscript𝑛2𝑟superscript𝑟3O(n^{2}r+r^{3})italic_O ( italic_n start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_r + italic_r start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ), which is comparatively slower than TISVD’s O⁢(n⁢r+r3)𝑂𝑛𝑟superscript𝑟3O(nr+r^{3})italic_O ( italic_n italic_r + italic_r start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ).

We have compared TISVD with the rank-k𝑘kitalic_k truncated SVD in Section 5.2. We further construct an experiment to test the performance of randomized SVD. We initialize a random Gaussian matrix 𝑨∈ℝ100×100𝑨superscriptℝ100100\bm{A}\in\mathbb{R}^{100\times 100}bold_italic_A ∈ blackboard_R start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 100 × 100 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT and use random Gaussian matrix B,C∈ℝm×100𝐵𝐶superscriptℝ𝑚100B,C\in\mathbb{R}^{m\times 100}italic_B , italic_C ∈ blackboard_R start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_m × 100 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT as low rank update. We set m=3,k=30formulae-sequence𝑚3𝑘30m=3,k=30italic_m = 3 , italic_k = 30 and update 𝑨𝑨\bm{A}bold_italic_A 500500500500 to 50000500005000050000 times respectively.

From Figure 4, we see that TISVD continues to show desirable decomposition performance. Both TIVD and randomized SVD can reduce the size of the decomposed matrix through the low-rank approximation matrix, thereby accelerating the algorithm. However, randomized SVD enjoys a time complexity of O⁢(n2⁢k+k3)𝑂superscript𝑛2𝑘superscript𝑘3O(n^{2}k+k^{3})italic_O ( italic_n start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_k + italic_k start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ), which is worse than O⁢(n⁢k+k3)𝑂𝑛𝑘superscript𝑘3O(nk+k^{3})italic_O ( italic_n italic_k + italic_k start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 3 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ). Besides, TISVD uses incremental updates to update the singular value matrix, which is more scalable for online learning algorithms based on incremental sketching.

The optimization error quantifies the discrepancy between the hypothesis generated by the proposed faster second-order online kernel learning algorithm and the optimal hypothesis on the incremental randomized sketches at each round. On the other hand, the estimation error measures the difference between the optimal hypotheses on the incremental randomized sketches for the first t𝑡titalic_t instances and for all T𝑇Titalic_T instances, respectively.

To obtain an upper bound for the optimization error, we leverage the directional curvature condition presented in Assumption 2. Appendix D Proof of Remark 2

Proof.

Appendix E Dataset and Experimental Setup

We evaluate FORKS on several real-world datasets for binary classification tasks. We use several well-known classification benchmarks for online learning, where the number of instances ranges from 1000100010001000 to 581,012581012581,012581 , 012. All the experiments are performed over 20 different random permutations of the datasets. Besides, we introduce a large-scale real-world dataset KuaiRec (Gao et al., 2022), which has 4,494,57844945784,494,5784 , 494 , 578 instances and associated timestamps. We do not tune the stepsizes η𝜂\etaitalic_η of all the gradient descent-based algorithms but take the value η=0.2𝜂0.2\eta=0.2italic_η = 0.2. We uniformly set d=1𝑑1d=1italic_d = 1, α=0.01𝛼0.01\alpha=0.01italic_α = 0.01, ηi=0subscript𝜂𝑖0\eta_{i}=0italic_η start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 0, σi=0.5subscript𝜎𝑖0.5\sigma_{i}=0.5italic_σ start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 0.5 and λ=0.01𝜆0.01\lambda=0.01italic_λ = 0.01 for FORKS and SkeGD. We take the Gaussian kernel κ⁢(𝒙i,𝒙j)=exp⁡(−‖𝒙i−𝒙j‖222⁢σ2)𝜅subscript𝒙𝑖subscript𝒙𝑗subscriptsuperscriptnormsubscript𝒙𝑖subscript𝒙𝑗222superscript𝜎2\kappa(\bm{x}_{i},\bm{x}_{j})=\exp\left(\frac{-||\bm{x}_{i}-\bm{x}_{j}||^{2}_{% 2}}{2\sigma^{2}}\right)italic_κ ( bold_italic_x start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT , bold_italic_x start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ) = roman_exp ( divide start_ARG - | | bold_italic_x start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_i end_POSTSUBSCRIPT - bold_italic_x start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_j end_POSTSUBSCRIPT | | start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT end_ARG start_ARG 2 italic_σ start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT end_ARG ) with parameter set σ∈{2[−5:+0.5:7]}𝜎superscript2delimited-[]:50.5:7\sigma\in\{2^{[-5:+0.5:7]}\}italic_σ ∈ { 2 start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT [ - 5 : + 0.5 : 7 ] end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT } used by (Zhang and Liao, 2019). All experiments are performed on a machine with 24-core Intel(R) Xeon(R) Gold 6240R 2.40GHz CPU and 256 GB memory.

Appendix F More about KuaiRec Dataset

For our experiment, we utilize KuaiRec’s small matrix as the dataset. The processing of dependent variables involves dividing the ratio of the user’s time spent on the video to the video duration (watch ratio) by a threshold of 0.75, with values greater than 0.75 classified as positive and values less than or equal to 0.75 classified as negative. The selection of independent variables is obtained from three csv files, as specified in the code.

Appendix G Additional Experiment Results

G.1. Additional Experiment Results under Adversarial Environment

We set b=500𝑏500b=500italic_b = 500, r=20𝑟20r=20italic_r = 20 for codrna-2 and german-2. The results are presented in Table 4.

We demonstrate that all methods exhibit improved performance in a less hostile adversarial setting. Nevertheless, FORKS remains superior to other algorithms with significant advantages in terms of both time and prediction performance.

G.2. Additional Experiment Results under Large-Scale Real-world Datasets

Similar to the experimental setup described in section 5.3, we evaluate the performance of the algorithms across various budgets B𝐵Bitalic_B, spanning from 100100100100 to 500500500500. To avoid excessive training time, we use a budgeted version of PROS-N-KONS with a maximum budget of Bmax=100subscript𝐵100B_{\max}=100italic_B start_POSTSUBSCRIPT roman_max end_POSTSUBSCRIPT = 100. Since the buffer size of PROS-N-KONS is data-dependent, we repeat the training process 20202020 times to compute the average error rate and the logarithm of the average time for comparison.

From Figure 5, we can observe that our FORKS show the best learning performance under most budget conditions. The large-scale experiments validate the effectiveness and efficiency of our proposed FORKS, making it potentially more practical than the existing second-order online kernel learning approaches. Meanwhile, we observed that increasing the budget size B𝐵Bitalic_B results in a lower mistake rate but also leads to a higher computation time cost. In practice, we can flexibly adjust the budget size based on our estimates of the data stream size to obtain a better approximation quality.
